"Brucet S., Boix D., Quintana X.D., Jensen E., Nathansen L.W., Trochine C., Meerhoff M., Gascó S., Jeppesen E.","Factors influencing zooplankton size structure at contrasting temperatures in coastal shallow lakes: Implications for effects of climate change",2010,"Limnology and Oceanography","55","4",,"1697","1711",,,10.4319/lo.2010.55.4.1697,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955643535&partnerID=40&md5=210f53d061f143d8f6a8bc68fcdd5596","Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark; European Commission, Joint Research Centre, Institute for Environment and Sustainability, Ispra, Italy; Institute of Aquatic Ecology and Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Girona, Campus de Montilivi, Girona, Spain; Laboratorio de Limnología, Instituto de Investigaciones en Biodiversidad y Medioambiente, Universidad Nacional del Comahue, Bariloche, Argentina; Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de la República, Montevideo, Uruguay","Brucet, S., Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark, European Commission, Joint Research Centre, Institute for Environment and Sustainability, Ispra, Italy, Institute of Aquatic Ecology and Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Girona, Campus de Montilivi, Girona, Spain; Boix, D., Institute of Aquatic Ecology and Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Girona, Campus de Montilivi, Girona, Spain; Quintana, X.D., Institute of Aquatic Ecology and Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Girona, Campus de Montilivi, Girona, Spain; Jensen, E., Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark; Nathansen, L.W., Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark; Trochine, C., Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark, Laboratorio de Limnología, Instituto de Investigaciones en Biodiversidad y Medioambiente, Universidad Nacional del Comahue, Bariloche, Argentina; Meerhoff, M., Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark, Departamento de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Universidad de la República, Montevideo, Uruguay; Gascó, S., Institute of Aquatic Ecology and Department of Environmental Sciences, University of Girona, Campus de Montilivi, Girona, Spain; Jeppesen, E., Department of Freshwater Ecology, National Environmental Research Institute, Aarhus University, Silkeborg, Denmark","We assessed the importance of temperature, salinity, and predation for the size structure of zooplankton and provided insight into the future ecological structure and function of shallow lakes in a warmer climate. Artificial plants were introduced in eight comparable coastal shallow brackish lakes located at two contrasting temperatures: cold-temperate and Mediterranean climate region. Zooplankton, fish, and macroinvertebrates were sampled within the plants and at open-water habitats. The fish communities of these brackish lakes were characterized by small-sized individuals, highly associated with submerged plants. Overall, higher densities of small planktivorous fish were recorded in the Mediterranean compared to the cold-temperate region, likely reflecting temperature-related differences as have been observed in freshwater lakes. Our results suggest that fish predation is the major control of zooplankton size structure in brackish lakes, since fish density was related to a decrease in mean body size and density of zooplankton and this was reflected in a unimodal shaped biomass-size spectrum with dominance of small sizes and low size diversity. Salinity might play a more indirect role by shaping zooplankton communities toward more salt-tolerant species. In a global-warming perspective, these results suggest that changes in the trophic structure of shallow lakes in temperate regions might be expected as a result of the warmer temperatures and the potentially associated increases in salinity. The decrease in the density of largebodied zooplankton might reduce the grazing on phytoplankton and thus the chances of maintaining the clear water state in these ecosystems. © 2010, by the American Society of Limnology and Oceanography, Inc.",,"aquatic plant; brackish water; coastal zone; fish; global warming; macroinvertebrate; Mediterranean environment; planktivore; predation; saline lake; salinity; shallow water; size structure; temperature profile; trophic structure; zooplankton",,,,,,"(1989) Standard Methods for the Examination of Water and Wastewater, , APHA] AMERICAN PUBLIC HEALTH ASSOCIATION., 17th ed. APHA; Badosa, A., Boix, D., Brucet, S., López-Flores, R., Gascón, S., Quintana, X.D., Zooplankton taxonomic and size diversity in Mediterranean coastal lagoons (NE Iberian Peninsula): Influence of hydrology, nutrient composition, food resource availability and predation (2007) Estuar. Coast. Shelf Sci., 71, pp. 335-346. , doi:10.1016/j.ecss.2006.08.005; Blanck, A., Lammouroux, N., Large-scale intraspecific variation in life-history traits of 44 European freshwater fish (2007) J. Biogeogr., 34, pp. 862-875. , doi:10.1111/j.1365-2699.2006. 01654.x; Blanco, S., Romo, S., Villena, M.J., Martínez, S., Fish communities and food web interactions in some shallow Mediterranean lakes (2003) Hydrobiologia, 506-509, pp. 473-480. , doi:10.1023/B:HYDR.0000008583.05327.da; Bottrell, H.H., Duncan, A., Gliwicz, Z.M., A review of some problems in zooplankton production studies (1976) Norw. J. Zool., 24, pp. 419-456; Brucet, S., Boix, D., López-Flores, R., Badosa, A., Morenoamich, R., Quintana, X.D., Zooplankton structure and dynamics in permanent and temporary Mediterranean salt marshes: Taxon-based and size-based approaches (20